# Frontend AI Agent Rules — RiskFeed Client

You are an exceptionally talented and thoughtful professional frontend developer. You write clean, maintainable, type-safe code following the conventions and patterns already established in this project. **Study the existing codebase before writing any code** — consistency with existing patterns is mandatory.

---

## 1. Technology Stack

This project uses the following core technologies. **Do not introduce alternative libraries** for any of these responsibilities without explicit approval:

| Responsibility        | Technology                                         |
| --------------------- | -------------------------------------------------- |
| Framework             | **React 19** with **TypeScript** (strict mode)     |
| Build Tool            | **Vite** (with `@vitejs/plugin-react-swc`)         |
| Styling               | **Tailwind CSS v4** (via `@tailwindcss/vite`)      |
| UI Components         | **Shadcn UI** (`new-york` style, Lucide icons)     |
| State Management      | **Redux Toolkit** + `redux-persist`                |
| Server State          | **TanStack React Query v5**                        |
| HTTP Client           | **Axios** (via the project's `api` client)         |
| Animation             | **Framer Motion**                                  |
| Routing               | **React Router DOM v7**                            |
| Forms                 | **React Hook Form** + **Zod** validation           |
| Notifications/Toasts  | **Sonner** (via `@/components/ui/sonner`)          |
| Icons                 | **Lucide React** and **React Icons**               |
| Error Monitoring      | **Sentry** (production only)                       |
| Real-time             | **Socket.IO Client**                               |

---

## 2. Project Structure & File Organization

Follow the existing directory structure strictly. Place files in the correct directories:

```
src/
├── api/                  # API layer (client, config, endpoints, services)
│   ├── client.ts         # Axios instance with interceptors — DO NOT DUPLICATE
│   ├── config.ts         # Environment-based API config
│   ├── api_endpoints.ts  # Centralized endpoint constants
│   ├── queryClient.ts    # TanStack Query client defaults
│   └── services/         # API service objects grouped by domain
├── components/
│   ├── ui/               # Shadcn UI primitives — DO NOT manually edit
│   └── [shared]/         # Reusable project components
├── config/               # App configuration (e.g., Sentry)
├── constants/            # App-wide constants (e.g., status styles)
├── context/              # React context providers
├── hooks/                # Custom React hooks
├── interfaces/           # TypeScript interfaces & DTOs
│   └── [domain]/
│       └── dto/          # Data Transfer Objects for API payloads
├── layout/               # Layout wrappers (e.g., DashboardLayout)
├── lib/                  # Utility libraries (e.g., cn() helper)
├── pages/                # Page-level components, grouped by role
│   ├── admin/
│   ├── contractor/
│   ├── public/
│   └── user/
├── routes/               # Route definitions, grouped by role
├── store/                # Redux store
│   ├── index.ts          # Store config with persistence
│   ├── hooks.ts          # Typed hooks (useAppDispatch, useAppSelector)
│   └── slices/           # Redux slices (use _template.ts as reference)
└── utils/                # General utility functions
```

### File Naming Conventions

- **Components**: PascalCase for component files (e.g., `ErrorBoundary.tsx`)
- **Shadcn UI components**: kebab-case (e.g., `alert-dialog.tsx`) — follow Shadcn's naming
- **Hooks**: kebab-case prefixed with `use-` (e.g., `use-auth.ts`, `use-mobile.ts`)
- **Redux slices**: camelCase suffixed with `Slice` (e.g., `authSlice.ts`)
- **Interfaces/DTOs**: kebab-case with `.interface.ts` or `.dto.ts` suffix
- **Utils/Services**: camelCase or PascalCase matching existing patterns
- **Constants**: kebab-case (e.g., `status-styles.ts`)

---

## 3. Styling & Theming

### Color Theme

- **Always use the project's CSS variable-based theme** defined in `src/index.css`.
- Reference theme colors using Tailwind utility classes mapped to CSS variables (e.g., `bg-primary`, `text-foreground`, `border-border`, `bg-card`, `text-muted-foreground`).
- The project supports **light and dark mode** via the `.dark` class on the root element.
- **Never hardcode color values** (hex, rgb, oklch) directly in components. Use the theme tokens.
- Only in exceptional circumstances where the design system tokens are insufficient should you use raw color values — and document why.

### Tailwind CSS v4

- Use Tailwind v4 conventions. The project imports `@tailwindcss` and `shadcn/tailwind.css` in `index.css`.
- Use the `cn()` utility from `@/lib/utils` to merge conditional class names.
- The project uses the **Inter** font family as its global typeface.

### Responsive Design

- Build **mobile-first** layouts.
- Use Tailwind's responsive prefixes (`sm:`, `md:`, `lg:`, `xl:`) for breakpoints.
- Reference `@/hooks/use-mobile.ts` for programmatic breakpoint detection when needed.

---

## 4. Component Development

### Shadcn UI Components

- **Use existing Shadcn UI components** from `@/components/ui/` before building custom ones.
- If a required Shadcn component doesn't exist, add it using the `shadcn` CLI (`npx shadcn@latest add <component>`).
- **Never manually edit** the files inside `@/components/ui/` — they are managed by Shadcn CLI.
- Import all Shadcn components with the `@/components/ui/` path alias.

### Loading States

- **Always** use the Shadcn `<Skeleton />` component from `@/components/ui/skeleton` for loading states when fetching data from API endpoints.
- Build skeleton loaders that structurally mirror the real component's layout (same widths, heights, spacing) for a polished shimmer effect.
- For full-page loading (lazy-loaded routes), use the `<Loading />` component from `@/components/ui/Loading`.

### Animation

- Use **Framer Motion** for entrance animations, transitions, and micro-interactions.
- Keep animations subtle and purposeful — avoid excessive or distracting motion.
- Use Framer Motion's `AnimatePresence` for mount/unmount transitions.

### Error Handling

- Wrap route-level content with the project's `<ErrorBoundary />` (already configured in `App.tsx`).
- Show user-friendly error states with retry options where appropriate.
- Use the `HandleAPIError` utility from `@/utils/HandleAPIError` for consistent API error handling.

---

## 5. State Management

### Redux Toolkit (Client State)

- Use Redux for **persistent, cross-component client state** (auth, user profile, theme, etc).
- **Always use typed hooks**: `useAppDispatch` and `useAppSelector` from `@/store/hooks`.
- When creating new slices, **copy `@/store/slices/_template.ts`** as a starting point.
- After creating a slice:
  1. Import and add the reducer to `rootReducer` in `@/store/index.ts`.
  2. Add to the `whitelist` array in `persistConfig` if the state should persist across sessions.
  3. Create a corresponding custom hook in `@/hooks/` if necessary.
- Keep slice state minimal — avoid duplicating server state in Redux.

### TanStack React Query (Server State)

- Use TanStack Query for **all server state** — data fetching, caching, mutations, and cache invalidation.
- Follow the established pattern in `@/hooks/use-auth.ts`:
  - `useQuery` for data fetching with descriptive `queryKey` arrays.
  - `useMutation` for create/update/delete operations.
  - Handle `onSuccess` callbacks to update Redux state and invalidate related queries via `queryClient.invalidateQueries()`.
  - Handle `onError` callbacks with `APIErrorResponse()` for consistent error toasts.
- Do not use `useEffect` + `useState` for data fetching — always prefer TanStack Query.
- Respect the default `staleTime` (5 min) and `gcTime` (10 min) configured in `@/api/queryClient.ts`.

### When to Use Which

| Use Case                           | Solution                      |
| ---------------------------------- | ----------------------------- |
| Auth tokens, user session          | Redux (persisted)             |
| User profile data, theme           | Redux (persisted)             |
| API response data, lists, details  | TanStack Query                |
| Form state                         | React Hook Form               |
| Component-local UI state           | `useState` / `useReducer`     |

---

## 6. API Layer

### HTTP Requests

- **Always use** the project's `api` client from `@/api/client.ts`. Never create new Axios instances.
- The client automatically handles:
  - Bearer token injection from cookies
  - Token refresh on new cookies from server
  - 401 redirects to login
  - 429 rate-limit retries
  - Sentry error capture for 500+ errors
  - Automatic retries for network failures (up to 3 attempts)

### API Endpoints

- Define all new endpoints in `@/api/api_endpoints.ts` as grouped constant objects.
- Never hardcode endpoint URLs in components, hooks, or services.

### API Services

- Create domain-specific service objects in `@/api/services/`.
- Follow the pattern in `@/api/services/auth.ts`:
  ```typescript
  import api from "../client";
  import API_ENDPOINTS from "../api_endpoints";

  const DomainApi = {
    getItems: () => api.get(API_ENDPOINTS.domain.getItems),
    createItem: (data: CreateItemDto) => api.post(API_ENDPOINTS.domain.createItem, data),
  };

  export default DomainApi;
  ```
- Mark unauthenticated requests explicitly with `{ authenticated: false }`.

---

## 7. Routing

- Use **lazy loading** (`React.lazy`) for all page-level components.
- Define routes using `RouteObject[]` arrays in the appropriate file under `@/routes/`:
  - `publicRoutes.tsx` — accessible without authentication
  - `userRoutes.tsx` — user role routes (wrapped in `DashboardLayout`)
  - `contractorRoutes.tsx` — contractor role routes
  - `adminRoutes.tsx` — admin role routes
- Authenticated routes are nested under the `<DashboardLayout />` component which provides the sidebar, header, and main content area via `<Outlet />`.
- Use the `@/` path alias for all imports in route files.

---

## 8. Forms & Validation

- Use **React Hook Form** with `@hookform/resolvers` for form management.
- Define validation schemas with **Zod**.
- Use Shadcn's `<Form />`, `<FormField />`, `<FormItem />`, `<FormLabel />`, `<FormControl />`, and `<FormMessage />` components for consistent form UI.
- For form submission, use TanStack Query mutations.

---

## 9. TypeScript Conventions

- Enable and respect **strict TypeScript** — no `any` types unless absolutely unavoidable (and annotate with `// eslint-disable-next-line @typescript-eslint/no-explicit-any`).
- Define interfaces in `@/interfaces/` grouped by domain.
- Use DTOs (Data Transfer Objects) in `@/interfaces/[domain]/dto/` for API request/response shapes.
- Export types using `export type` / `export interface` (project uses `verbatimModuleSyntax`).
- Use `import type` for type-only imports to ensure they are erased at build time.
- Use the `@/` path alias for all imports — never use relative paths that go more than one level up (`../../`).

---

## 10. Notifications & Toasts

- Use **Sonner** for all toast notifications via the `toast` function from `sonner`.
- The `<Toaster />` is already configured globally in `App.tsx` with `richColors` and `position="top-right"`.
- Use descriptive toast messages:
  - `toast.success()` for successful operations
  - `toast.error()` for failures
  - `toast.loading()` for in-progress states

---

## 11. Error Handling Patterns

- Use the `APIErrorResponse` utility from `@/utils/HandleAPIError` in all mutation `onError` callbacks.
- For UI-level error boundaries, use the existing `<ErrorBoundary />` component.
- Never swallow errors silently — always provide user feedback.

---

## 12. Code Quality & Best Practices

- **No console.log in production code** — use Sentry for error tracking.
- **No unused imports or variables** — the project enforces `noUnusedLocals` and `noUnusedParameters` in TypeScript.
- **Use functional components** with hooks — no class components.
- **Prefer `const` arrow functions** for component definitions.
- **Keep components focused** — extract logic into custom hooks, extract reusable UI into shared components.
- **Use `cn()`** for conditional class concatenation — never string interpolation for Tailwind classes.
- **Use descriptive naming** for variables, functions, and components.
- Run `npm run build` before considering a feature complete to ensure zero TypeScript errors.
- Follow the existing ESLint configuration — do not disable rules without justification.

---

## 13. Import Order Convention

Follow this import ordering:

```typescript
// 1. React and React ecosystem
import { useState, useEffect } from "react";

// 2. Third-party libraries
import { motion } from "framer-motion";
import { useQuery, useMutation } from "@tanstack/react-query";
import { toast } from "sonner";

// 3. Internal absolute imports (@/)
import { Button } from "@/components/ui/button";
import { Skeleton } from "@/components/ui/skeleton";
import { useAppSelector } from "@/store/hooks";
import api from "@/api/client";
import type { UserInterface } from "@/interfaces/user/user.interface";

// 4. Relative imports (if any)
import { localHelper } from "./helpers";

// 5. Styles & assets (if any)
import logo from "../assets/images/logo.png";
```

---

## 14. Quick Reference: Do's and Don'ts

### ✅ Do

- Use Shadcn `<Skeleton />` for all loading states during data fetching
- Use TanStack Query for all API data fetching
- Use Redux for persistent client state only
- Use the `api` client from `@/api/client.ts` for all HTTP requests
- Use `cn()` from `@/lib/utils` for conditional classes
- Use Framer Motion for animations
- Use Sonner `toast` for user notifications
- Use CSS variable theme tokens for colors
- Use `import type` for type-only imports
- Use the `@/` path alias for all imports
- Create skeleton loaders that mirror the real component layout
- Lazy load all page components
- Define all API endpoints in `api_endpoints.ts`

### ❌ Don't

- Don't create new Axios instances — use the shared `api` client
- Don't hardcode hex/rgb color values — use theme variables
- Don't use `useEffect` + `useState` for API data fetching
- Don't manually edit files inside `@/components/ui/`
- Don't use `any` without ESLint disable annotation
- Don't use `useDispatch`/`useSelector` directly — use `useAppDispatch`/`useAppSelector`
- Don't hardcode API URLs — use `API_ENDPOINTS`
- Don't import from `react-redux` directly in components — use the typed hooks
- Don't put server state in Redux — that's what TanStack Query is for
- Don't skip loading/error states — every data-dependent UI needs both
- Don't skip form validation — always use Zod schemas with React Hook Form
- Don't introduce new libraries without explicit approval


